Part 3. Decision Making with Interpolation


3.1 Order of Operations: When we interpolate data, we must work through an order of operations.

Visual Summary courtesy of Esri



3.2 Key Assumptions: Just like with statistics (thatâs what interpolation is behind the scenes!), we have to explore our data ahead of time to get a better understanding of it to make analysis decisions. There are several key assumptions to verify through Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis (ESDA)

âââa. Are the data representative of a Continuous surface? Is there a value everywhere in the surface? Think about rainfall over an area. Even if itâs NOT raining, a 0 measurement is still a value. Temperature is also helpful to think about. There isnât ever NOT temperature.

âââb. Is there Spatial Autocorrelation? With spatial autocorrelation, things that are closer together are more closely related (Waldo Toblerâs First Law of Geography!)

âââc.Â Is there Stationarity? For any two points, their consistent distance from eachother is most important. Specific (x,y,z) location doesnât matter. Distance explains correlation.

âââd.Â Does the data have Normal Distribution? Data, if plotted in a chart, should have a nice bell-curve shape, with 95% of data falling within the first two standard deviations.

âââe. Is there No Spatial Clustering? Data should be randomly or regularly spaced over the surface.

âââf.Â Are there Global Trends? A fixed, non-random (deterministic) trend in the data explains large scale variation in your phenomenon- like how elevation may influence temperature. That relationship occurs globally.

3.3 Create a Prediction Surface This middle step of the full process is where you create your interpolated data. In part 4 below, you will explore data to better understand some key assumptions, then youâll create a prediction surface in part 5- your interpolated data!

3.4 Cross Validate After running your interpolation, it is critical to cross-validate your results! Were your predicted values comparable to the measured values (aka âsanity checkâ). Weâll do this in Part 6. You can also run other interpolation methods to see if you get similar results.

How to Choose a Method of Interpolation

Phenomena can be measured in various ways depending on your analysis goal.

The data type of a measured phenomenon determines which geostatistical interpolation methods apply to the analysis. However, the cross-validation metrics and graphs should be evaluated to ensure that the prediction surface is valid.

âââ2D Surfaces: x coordinate, y coordinate, value for thing being measured

âââ3D Surfaces: x coordinate, y coordinate, z coordinate (aka elevation)
âââand value for thing being measured

âââPolygon Surfaces: reaggregate (up or downscale) polygons to fill in missing data

Part 7. Spatial Estimation using a Species Distribution Model

Your summer project is funded by Bigfoot Field Researchers Organization (BFRO). BFRO receives funds from Big Foot enthusiastsâ donations, however the organization has recently decided to sell tourist packages for wilderness. Big Foot fanatics to bring in additional revenue to support additional Big Foot research endeavors.

Your job as the GIS analysts is to identify where BFRO and tourists will be most likely to spot (and hopefully get a picture) of the elusive Big Foot (aka Sasquatch or Yeti) in North America by creating a Species Distribution Model (SDM)(aka Ecological Niche Model).

SDMs assume that you can predict the entire, or potential, spatial distribution of a phenomenon, by relating the sites of known occurrence (Big Foot sightings) with predictor variables known for these sites and all other sites. A common application of this method is to predict species ranges with climate/environmental data as predictors. The following steps are usually taken:

âââââ¢ Acquire locations of species occurrence and environmental data
âââââ¢ The known species locations and environmental data are used to fit a model predicting likelihood of presence (or abundance) of the species
âââââ¢ The model is used to predict the likelihood of presence across an area of interest (sometimes in the future or past).

7.5 Determine if your predictor variables are correlated
It is important to know if your predictor variables (temperature, precipitation, and elevation) are correlated with each other. Many models assume that predictor variables are not correlated. When variables are correlated and your model assumes independence, any results derived from the model are considered uncertain/invalid. This step helps modelers decide what type of model is appropriate for the type of data they are using so they do not invalidate model assumptions.

8.2 Variable Importance Plots:
One important output from Random Forest models is called a Variable Importance Plot/Charts. These plots inform you of how important each individual predictor variable was for modeling the dependent variable (Big Foot Sightings), on a scale from 0 (unimportant) to 1 (very important) (i.e.Â how important was temperature, precipitation, and elevation were to predict Big Foot presence in North America).

A variable with low importance essentially does nothing to help train the model, and if removed when training a model, does not alter the predictive power when all variables are used in the model. This is important for people who use âBig Dataâ, as they can remove uninformative data and reduce computational power and time.

Part 9: Validating Your Modelâs Predictive Power


After training/calibrating a model, it is standard to test/validate the results of your model before using the model to predict the dependent variable on a larger dataset. ArcGIS Pro is still developing their validation toolsets, so Dr.Â Bailey Morrison, a Bigfoot modelling expert, has provided you with summary statistics computed using the statistical software R.


Model Evaluation Numbers:
Statistic: Area Under Curve (AUC) = 0.88
Statistic: Pearsonâs Correlation = 0.66


What do these values mean?

Pearsonâs Correlation:
Pearsonâs Correlation ranges between -1 and 1, where 0 is no correlation, 1 is total positive correlation, and -1 is total negative correlation. For example, a positive correlation near 1 indicates that the observed Big Foot sightings are nearly identical to Big Foot presence predicted by your model. Generally, a correlation value >= 0.7 indicates a positive and significant relationship between the observed and predicted data.

AUC:
The Area Under the Curve (AUC) value is a measure of the ability of a classifier (your Random Forest Model) to distinguish between classes (Big Foot Presence vs.Â Absence) and is a summary statistic for an ROC Curve. The higher the AUC, the better the model is at distinguishing between positive and negative classes. When AUC = 1, the model is able to perfectly distinguish between all Big Foot presence and absence points correctly. If, however, the AUC = 0, then your model is predicting all Big Foot presences as absences and vice versa.

ROC Curves:
Lastly, the ROC curve is a plot of True Positive Rate (TPR) on the y-axis vs.Â the False Positive Rate (FPR, specificity) on the x-axis and is great for analyzing the strength/predictive power of a classified model. The job of your random forest model is to assign higher probabilities to observations that are Big Foot presence (1) and lower probabilities to observations that are Big Foot absences (0). The ROC curve of a good, classified model should therefore be closer to the top left of the graph. (See image below).

Part 11: Interpreting Your Model Results


You now have a fully rasterized map of Big Footâs distribution in North America. Your big_foot point shapefile contained only the discrete values 1 (Present) and 0 (Absent). However, this new map contains continuous values ranging from 0-1.

The bigfoot_dist_rf.crf rasterâs values indicate the Probability of Occurrence of Big Foot for each raster cell.
âââââ¢ A value of 0 indicates that you will have a 0% change of finding Big Foot at that pixel
âââââ¢ A value of 1 indicates you will have a 100% chance of finding Big Foot at that Pixel
âââââ¢ A value of 0.5 indicates that you will have a 50% chance of finding Big Foot at that pixel.

The question that should be on your mind is: at what probability of occurrence will I actually find Big Foot?

The AUC value from the previous section (0.88) is a good threshold metric that can be used to reclassify your modeled Big Foot distribution from continuous values back to discrete absence/presence values.

Where bigfoot_dist_rf.crf pixels >= 0.88, the pixels will be reclassified to 1 (present). Where bigfoot_dist_rf.crf pixels are <0.88, the pixels will be reclassified to 0 (absent).

1. Analysis ribbon -> Tools -> Toolboxes -> Image Analyst Tools -> Map Algebra -> Raster Calculator
2. In the equation box type (or copy + paste):
3. Con( âbigfoot_dist_rf.crfâ<= 0.88, 1, 0)
4. Output Raster = bigfoot_dist_NA 5. Run



You should now have a new raster layer called bigfoot_dist_NA that only contains 1 for Present and 0 for Absent. Feel free to change the color scheme of this raster layer where you can clearly see the difference between Big Foot presence/absence.
